Douglass speaks right on; you acknowledge him to have been on the ground—nay, to
                  have gone over the field; Ward seeks for and finds the corners;
                  sticks the stakes, and leaves them standing; we know where to find them.

Every maiden who prefers in marriage a rich suitor of doubtful morals or scanty
                  brains to a poor one, of sound principles, blameless life, good information and
                  sound sense;

Every young man who, in choosing the sharer of his fireside and the future mother
                  of his children, is less solicitous as to what she is good for, than as to how
                  much she is worth;

Every youth who is trained to regard little work and much recompense—short
                  business-hours and long dinners—as the chief ends of exertion and as assurances of
                  a happy life;
